And now, I want to
find something from--

00:41:57.790 --> 00:41:59.800
PowerPoint is not liking me.

00:41:59.800 --> 00:42:01.470
Minimize that.

00:42:01.470 --> 00:42:04.400
Find QuickTime Player.

00:42:04.400 --> 00:42:05.540
Sorry, I just have to--

00:42:08.984 --> 00:42:09.484
aah!

00:42:14.907 --> 00:42:15.893
So that's the ship.

00:42:21.316 --> 00:42:25.780
This is a journalist with
a drone who went along

00:42:25.780 --> 00:42:26.860
with us on the last--

00:42:26.860 --> 00:42:28.461
so it's a desk job.

00:42:28.461 --> 00:42:29.585
It's a hell of a good desk.

00:42:35.200 --> 00:42:38.154
Yeah, and so basically I'm
tech support on a ship.

00:42:38.154 --> 00:42:39.820
Officially, I'm a
systems administrator.

00:42:39.820 --> 00:42:43.540
But in practice,
what I'm doing is

00:42:43.540 --> 00:42:46.390
rewriting the data
acquisition system

00:42:46.390 --> 00:42:48.790
that runs all of the sensors.

00:42:48.790 --> 00:42:51.610
And we've actually
convinced the NSF

00:42:51.610 --> 00:42:54.280
to allow us to open source
it, so research vessels

00:42:54.280 --> 00:43:00.790
all over the world can work
with a common bit of code.

00:43:00.790 --> 00:43:02.833
OK, let's see if I close it up--

00:43:02.833 --> 00:43:03.640
"doop."

00:43:03.640 --> 00:43:06.030
OK, next question.

00:43:06.030 --> 00:43:08.770
AUDIENCE: So when you did
the machine learning class,

00:43:08.770 --> 00:43:12.690
another nonfiction, one of
the things you have to do

00:43:12.690 --> 00:43:14.940
is make things unambiguous.

00:43:14.940 --> 00:43:16.860
But when you do
the short stories,

00:43:16.860 --> 00:43:18.360
it seems like you
were intentionally

00:43:18.360 --> 00:43:21.753
making things ambiguous.

00:43:21.753 --> 00:43:23.620
And what do you
think about that?

00:43:23.620 --> 00:43:26.430
DAVID PABLO COHN:
That's a good question.

00:43:26.430 --> 00:43:30.357
So do you want, like, caramel
or double-dark chocolate?

00:43:30.357 --> 00:43:31.440
AUDIENCE: Oh, double-dark.

00:43:31.440 --> 00:43:31.939
Yeah.

00:43:31.939 --> 00:43:34.020
DAVID PABLO COHN: OK.

00:43:34.020 --> 00:43:36.104
There are plenty of
these for more questions,

00:43:36.104 --> 00:43:38.520
if somebody else wants to get
on queue while I work on it.

00:43:41.365 --> 00:43:42.790
I hadn't thought about that.

00:43:46.030 --> 00:43:50.680
So some of my stories are--

00:43:50.680 --> 00:43:52.960
I guess what it is is
it's paying attention

00:43:52.960 --> 00:43:56.950
to what information
the words convey

00:43:56.950 --> 00:43:59.260
and being very tuned
into the nuances,

00:43:59.260 --> 00:44:03.400
so that if you want to be very
clear, you can be very clear.

00:44:03.400 --> 00:44:05.110
And if you want
to be unclear, you

00:44:05.110 --> 00:44:08.110
can basically say, warning,
warning-- ambiguity.

00:44:08.110 --> 00:44:10.750
And the other person
will actually know.

00:44:10.750 --> 00:44:13.300
So yeah, maybe it's
just trying to be tuned

00:44:13.300 --> 00:44:15.972
into the nuances of the words.

00:44:15.972 --> 00:44:17.430
I hadn't thought
about that before.

00:44:17.430 --> 00:44:18.130
Thank you.

00:44:18.130 --> 00:44:19.588
And I need to get
you [INAUDIBLE]..

00:44:19.588 --> 00:44:22.180
AUDIENCE: In brief, do you
like, actually, writing?

00:44:22.180 --> 00:44:25.720
Or do you enjoy the more the
responses to your writing?

00:44:25.720 --> 00:44:27.100
DAVID PABLO COHN: I like--

00:44:27.100 --> 00:44:31.640
actually, I don't particularly
like the sitting down

00:44:31.640 --> 00:44:33.070
and plowing through.

00:44:33.070 --> 00:44:36.310
What I like is when
I get that hook.

00:44:36.310 --> 00:44:39.736
It's sort of like when you're
surfing and you're-- paddle,

00:44:39.736 --> 00:44:40.360
paddle, paddle.

00:44:40.360 --> 00:44:40.880
And you don't get in.

00:44:40.880 --> 00:44:43.505
Paddle, paddle-- and then, when
you paddle and you get the wave

00:44:43.505 --> 00:44:45.160
and you see where
the story is going

00:44:45.160 --> 00:44:47.020
and it's just crashing
towards the end

00:44:47.020 --> 00:44:50.470
and you hit that last
line, you go, yeah!

00:44:50.470 --> 00:44:52.310
nailed it!

00:44:52.310 --> 00:44:54.130
That's the real endorphin thing.

00:44:54.130 --> 00:44:58.530
And yeah, hadn't
thought about that.

00:44:58.530 --> 00:44:59.030
Cool.

00:44:59.030 --> 00:44:59.330
Good question.

00:44:59.330 --> 00:44:59.940
Oh right.

00:44:59.940 --> 00:45:02.640
So I've got a couple more of
the dark chocolate and a bunch

00:45:02.640 --> 00:45:04.890
of the caramelie things.

00:45:04.890 --> 00:45:05.450
Oh!

00:45:05.450 --> 00:45:06.200
AUDIENCE: Caramel.

00:45:06.200 --> 00:45:07.730
DAVID PABLO COHN: OK.

00:45:07.730 --> 00:45:09.470
I think they're caramel.

00:45:09.470 --> 00:45:10.430
AUDIENCE: Chocolate.

00:45:10.430 --> 00:45:13.280
DAVID PABLO COHN: Dark, yes.

00:45:13.280 --> 00:45:15.570
Whoop.

00:45:15.570 --> 00:45:16.565
Anyone else?

00:45:16.565 --> 00:45:17.290
We good?

00:45:17.290 --> 00:45:19.760
Oop.

00:45:19.760 --> 00:45:23.020
And I can give you a
couple more paragraphs

00:45:23.020 --> 00:45:24.290
at the end, once we're done.

00:45:24.290 --> 00:45:25.390
AUDIENCE: So you
describe the way

00:45:25.390 --> 00:45:27.040
you do your short
novel by having

00:45:27.040 --> 00:45:28.362
an interesting first sentence.

00:45:28.362 --> 00:45:29.320
DAVID PABLO COHN: Yeah.

00:45:29.320 --> 00:45:30.820
AUDIENCE: Do you
think, if you could

00:45:30.820 --> 00:45:33.587
invent six interesting
sentences like that, turn that

00:45:33.587 --> 00:45:35.050
into a novel, saying they all--

00:45:35.050 --> 00:45:35.230
DAVID PABLO COHN: No.

00:45:35.230 --> 00:45:37.146
AUDIENCE: --have to be
part of the same thing?

00:45:37.146 --> 00:45:38.780
DAVID PABLO COHN:
No, the problem

00:45:38.780 --> 00:45:42.010
is that I can't seem to
get stuff to hold together.

00:45:45.418 --> 00:45:48.970
I have a novel that I've
rewritten four times now.

00:45:48.970 --> 00:45:52.630
And it's just, like, there are
these beautiful short arcs,

00:45:52.630 --> 00:45:54.490
but they don't line up.

00:45:54.490 --> 00:45:57.230
I can't get the person--

00:45:57.230 --> 00:46:00.880
he's supposed to be
in Monrovia, Liberia.

00:46:00.880 --> 00:46:04.120
But the way the story
goes, he's in Thailand

00:46:04.120 --> 00:46:05.770
with absolutely no--

00:46:05.770 --> 00:46:06.940
why would he go to--

00:46:06.940 --> 00:46:09.230
why would he go to--

00:46:09.230 --> 00:46:11.500
yah!

00:46:11.500 --> 00:46:13.210
And these two
people actually are

00:46:13.210 --> 00:46:16.030
supposed to be the same
person for this arc to work.

00:46:16.030 --> 00:46:17.486
And I can't--

00:46:17.486 --> 00:46:19.732
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
Martin has a process

00:46:19.732 --> 00:46:24.940
where he rewrites every novel,
like, umpteen times, which

00:46:24.940 --> 00:46:26.072
is why it's slow.

00:46:26.072 --> 00:46:27.280
DAVID PABLO COHN: Yeah, yeah.

00:46:27.280 --> 00:46:27.730
AUDIENCE: But a writ--

00:46:27.730 --> 00:46:29.990
AUDIENCE: Maybe eventually,
it will work out.

00:46:29.990 --> 00:46:31.315
Oh, sorry.

00:46:31.315 --> 00:46:33.520
AUDIENCE: A writer's
existential question-- once you

00:46:33.520 --> 00:46:36.280
have those eight
sentences, how long do

00:46:36.280 --> 00:46:38.830
you think it would be before
you can throw a machine learning

00:46:38.830 --> 00:46:43.370
process at it and come out with
stories where it's hard to tell

00:46:43.370 --> 00:46:47.740
whether I wrote it, Pablo wrote
it, or a machine in the cloud

00:46:47.740 --> 00:46:49.390
wrote it?

00:46:49.390 --> 00:46:52.180
DAVID PABLO COHN: I've
read some draft novels

00:46:52.180 --> 00:46:54.340
that I think were at
that point already.

00:46:54.340 --> 00:46:55.641
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:56.140 --> 00:46:59.410
I guess the question
is, how long will it

00:46:59.410 --> 00:47:01.540
be before we can
get something where

00:47:01.540 --> 00:47:04.882
we can't tell who wrote it and
we'd actually like to read.

00:47:04.882 --> 00:47:05.465
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:47:08.864 --> 00:47:11.280
DAVID PABLO COHN: Yeah, I think
we're actually out of time

00:47:11.280 --> 00:47:12.270
here.

00:47:12.270 --> 00:47:14.070
So anyone else?

00:47:14.070 --> 00:47:14.820
Thank you so much.

00:47:14.820 --> 00:47:15.120
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:15.120 --> 00:47:16.020
[APPLAUSE]

00:47:16.020 --> 00:47:17.570
AUDIENCE: Whoo!

